<h2 id="replace_copy_if"><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">replace_copy_if</code></h2>

<p>Finally, letâ€™s have a quick look at <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">replace_copy_if</code>. Iâ€™m sure you can guess what it does and how it accepts its parameters after just having read about <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">replace_copy</code> and <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">replace_if</code>. It works the same way as <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">replace_copy</code>, but instead of the fourth parameter defining the old value, it accepts a unary predicate, just like <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">replace_if</code>.</p>

<p>As a reminder, a unary predicate can be a pointer to a function, a functor or a <a href="">lambda exprssion</a>. I always use the latter in my examples as they are so short.</p>

